<br>
i asked a couple of my friends, and after they finished recoiling in horror (&quot;He wants to do <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> what</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->!!?&quot;) they suggested that what you're after might be a lot more than something obvious you just never learned.<br>
<br>
It was suggested you might want to try unicode?  There's a web page <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.unicode.org/">www.unicode.org/</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> (and a case study: <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://members.ozemail.com.au/~andjc/papers/cn99.html">members.ozemail.com.au/~andjc/papers/cn99.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->) which should have some details.  Otherwise, i have heard such divergent opinions, from your needing a japanese os/japanese html editor to &quot;oh, he can just do it on a regular mac with the japanese language pack!&quot;.  Otherwise, i think windows XP/frontpage XP should let you do what you're after without too much fuss.<br>
<br>
As for your second question, as many people have noted in the past, there's no subsitute for a good teacher.  So I would highly recommend that if you're serious about studying the language that you sign up for a class (audit a university course, etc.) or else get a tutor/pen pal etc.  Trust me, it helps!  That being said, when i studied abroad in japan, the only two books that went with me (besides my textbook and kanji dictionary) (ok, ok, and &quot;Making out in Japanese&quot; (which is useless by the way, my gf cracked up reading it))were &quot;A Dictionary of Basic Japanese Grammer&quot; and &quot;A Dictionary of Intermediate Japanese Grammer&quot;.  I cannot sufficiently stress how helpful these two books are.  I would recommend that you pick up the basic one first, despite its name, it will carry for at least 2 years in your japanese education.  It's pretty expensive, but it is worth its weight in gold.  It can be found on Amazon at <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/4789004546/qid=1017630104/sr=8-1/ref=sr_8_19_1/102-9150951-8932936">www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/4789004546/qid=1017630104/sr=8-1/ref=sr_8_19_1/102-9150951-8932936</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
(i hope that link works).  As for colloquilisms, I'm not so sure.  I had bought a couple of books in the past (something like &quot;More Japanese slang&quot; or something, by peter constantine) but they pretty much all sucked.  Nowadays i generally just ask my girlfriend if i have a question, but i'd like to get my hands on a good book on colloquialisms as well.  <br>
<br>
One of the books which I've found incredibly useful, albiet more specialized is &quot;Nihongo Pera! Pera!&quot; (amazon link) <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0804818908/qid%3D1017630770/ref%3Dsr%5F11%5F0%5F1/102-9150951-8932936">www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0804818908/qid%3D1017630770/ref%3Dsr%5F11%5F0%5F1/102-9150951-8932936 </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> which provides a comprehensive listing +definitions/examples of just about any japanese onomatopoeia you could ever want to know.  It definitely helps you sound more natural when you speak, I think, especially given the prevalence of onomatopoeia in the japanese language.  <br>
<br>
Hope that helps!<br>
<br>
