<br>
well, close.  actually there's a &quot;N&quot; sound in japanese (the only consanant without a vowel/ variously pronounced &quot;nn&quot; and &quot;mm&quot; depending on the context).   I would think that:<br>
 <br>
ジュスチン  (jusuchin) <br>
<br>
would be a little bit better, since the &quot;tin&quot; from &quot;justin&quot; would translate as &quot;chi&quot; (チ) and &quot;n&quot; (ン).  So you don't need to use the &quot;no&quot; sound at the end.  <br>
<br>
anyway, no i'm not a student at wesli, lol my english is pretty good already, i hope!! *(o.O)*v  (well at least i hope i'm past the point where i need to take an ESL class!)<br>
<br>
i'm actually at student at UW.  *sigh*  actually, they have an excellent japanese program if you were ever thinking of attending, though they are hands down the hardest classes i have*ever* taken in my entire college career.  worth it through, if you don't mind going to class 10 times a week and spending twice that amount of time doing homework. . . *grins* (maimai is a masochist)<br>
